The primary goals of this program are to determine the properties of the local population of white dwarf stars.  White dwarfs are planet-sized stars of enormous density that remain after stars like the sun exhaust their nuclear fuel and ædieÆ.   This is a volume-limited sample of nearby (&lt;25 pc) white dwarfs that can be studied by direct detection of stars within this distance with a high degree of completeness.  Population properties such as binary status, space density, space motions, mass distributions, luminosity functions and relatively unbiased spectral subsamples are directly defined by this technique.   An additional goal was to enhance and expand the contents of the Villanova White Dwarf Catalog.
We have identified approximately 85% of all white dwarfs out to 20 pc and 70% out to a distance of 25 pc and have expanded the Villanova White Dwarf Catalog to a total of 14,294 stars.  Specific outcomes include a detailed study of the space motions of the local sample showing that most nearby white dwarfs originate within the æthin galactic diskÆ and  display common kinematic properties, regardless of white dwarf spectral type. Other outcomes include a first catalog of Sirius-Like systems (main sequence stars like the sun with white dwarf companions).   This catalog clearly demonstrates that many more of these systems remain to be found beyond 20 pc.  It also allows a first time estimate of the space density of such systems.  A second study showed how it is possible to make much more precise empirical estimates of white dwarf masses and radii for white dwarfs in binary systems.  Such mass and radius estimates are critical to empirical verifications of the theoretical mass-radius relations for white dwarfs as well as for estimates of how much mass stars of various types loose in becoming white dwarfs.



